The devices to track people are increasingly being asked by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child is making people more and more think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can as well be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases such as that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of matches but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even though the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We strive to tell everyone that it is not spying but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of bad use of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," adds Pilin.
In his view, children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in case of emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova points out that if the child doesn't want to bring something like this to him, he'll get rid of it.
'And even smaller ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something when they don't want to be under control.'
"Mobile phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very questionable.
"If it's a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything he can to keep the child from having an electronic device to locate him."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as trace devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," said the psychologist.
It also confesses that such devices can help when an attack is not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, who offers tracking services for both cars and people, he claims that having such a device can help, even if it is destroyed in the case of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on regular emission after a specified period."
"In case the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
'The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in an extended position without moving', says Cech.
According to him, smartphones called intelligent phones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after they have formed it with a special proficiency.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to the one that is being worn in pendant of the size of a lightbox or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll figure it out after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for drawing cars.
This is a combination of systems for acquiring a position using GPS (which is commonly used as a self-sustainment) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
