A longer index than the annular is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men with longer index than the annull are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the hormone male testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple risk test for prostate cancer, especially for men before 60 years of age," proclaimed the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo prostate cancer test, including by combining genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, added Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the annullary.
For them as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those with the longest index the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60, the risk decrease reached 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two fingers quoted - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
