Can civilization bring the cleavages closer together?
After a campaign marked by invetiveness and negativity, a minimum of civilization broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a foreword of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not cause any breakthrough on the big issues to be dealt with during the session of the "Boyy Dog".
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to mark points. empty notation point partisan.
The commission's Wednesday public meeting on the President's deficit was also civilized, despite the political differences that remain among the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but that still divides members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both parties are now in a period of testing and testing each other to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of demands or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Both parties remain within miles of taxation, spending, health care or rights.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed over the tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now next to the Ethics and Public Policy Centre.
"It's inevitable after the elections.
Elections give rise to partisan passions and then disappear.
That's good."
On certain issues, including those on the agenda of the "boitous duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax reductions will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of it.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve a part or whole, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is likely to be made on the extension of unemployment benefits, because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of reducing taxes on the rich, while refusing unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is set on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "boxy duck", with the ratification of the "New START" Pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warned that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing problems of the "lame Duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress will meet in January.
Instead, he said, a period of disagreement is likely, even inevitable.
"Once the things that must be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civilization would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what happens between today and 2012 as a pre-show or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the Chamber and to the electors present in the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new Health Care Act.
These partisan positions are now clear in the first reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, reversing the retirement age and reducing expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, in their own opinion, imposed the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plans as an official recommendation, and they have had difficulty reaching that number.
The highest resistance remains among the group's elected members; this suggests that there is little reason or will to compromise on tax matters, at least today.
Galston foresees two phases in the fights between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first one will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, given that the Republicans are challenging Obama with regard to budget, tax and health care; then being followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is widely demonstrated that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans always want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the response of the public.
The one who will be judged to be lost will have to change his mind and find compromises.
However, that would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of the two parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, this week's civilization could be appreciated by many Americans.
But much more effort will be required from both sides to find a ground of understanding on the issues that still divide them.
