The European Union changes the rules for obtaining the visa
People must go to Service Centres for Visa Applicants prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011 the process of visa processing at the Embassy and Consulates of the United States will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will provide some advantages for the aspirants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, there will no longer be a need to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the visa processing and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspiring will make a single payment that will cover the three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Persons wishing to renew their visas will not have to engage in an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves to the nearest AUC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken into the CSA, applicants wishing to make a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bolletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
