A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
Yesterday, the United Nations proposed a domestic, commercial and industrial lighting renovation plan in Cancún in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas reduction (GHG) that corresponds to nearly a third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan lies in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to yesterday's plan, if the incandescent bulbs which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diodes bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to enlighten humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of the world's emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the planetary car park emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major issuing countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt balance in order to stabilize by 2020 the increase in climate at 2 degrees centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy disappears in heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With fluocompact bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs average 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturing Philips this week - this company has also participated in the United Nations study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the economy possible with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats as well as emit very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown reservations to fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and they need to be eliminated as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluocompact bulb, but rather coal thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce spent electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion.
