Hackers revengers and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears only as a scandal in the face of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" U.S. revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what could be read for months in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's sinister caricature profile was for long time for cabaret artists sketch material.
The rule that secret records should be composed only of news already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templers or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And that is not only because the author of hidden texts does not like to do unprecedented research (he does not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who go to occultism only believe in what they already know, and who confirm what they have already learned.
It's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
Same for secret files.
The informer is lazy, and lazy (or limited in mind) the chief of secret services (unless he could be, I know, editor at Libération), who retains only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the State Department was the same as the newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the Heads of State can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have become spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it's only through hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy under bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a welcome blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put the victims as much in crisis as the "boreals".
But let's come to the deep nature of what happened.
So, in Orwell's time, we could conceive all power like a Big Brother who was controlling every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy has been fully proven since, in order to control each movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as a citizen's revenger - may know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets keep?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret of secrecy, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks didn't do any harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made too much damage to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on line any information reserved - this would be published on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports by telephone.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that for now, my forecast is about science fiction and is therefore Romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government officials who travel discreetly in uncontrollable routes, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at the very least, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in key closed drawers: the Watergate's spying attempt has been less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now progressing in crabs, i.e. backstage.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized the communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephones).
Video cassettes (analogics) had allowed cinema researchers to explore a step-by-step film, going forward and backwards and discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now CDs (numerics) allow only to jump from chapter to chapter, that is, by macro portions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while on the plane, and the travels it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that communication policies and techniques return to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was being done in the secret of the embassies.
It is now the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: How France Bidouille’s Promises of Financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review compliance with the promises of fast-disbursed funding (such fast-start or early-start funding) carried out by developed countries.
And the big French bidouillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU came out of the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated for its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that in 2010 EUR 2.2 billion has been released, which puts it on the right track for compliance with its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look at the detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of public development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonization, some Member States of which France had blocked the procedure.
Today, each one chooses the reference that is best suited to him.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the funding of "all new projects" of the year 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or to the overall level of Public Development Assistance.
In effect, France's total support for developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element, the distribution between gifts and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that €1 loaned is equal to €1 given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some profitable investments (often projects related to emission mitigation based on more efficient technologies), it is a mistake to present a euro that will be recovered as an equivalent to a euro given... Moreover, it should only be counted on under its commitments as the cost of lending for the lender country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has only made such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) comply with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts €1 to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-through tour!
In summary, in its fast-start funding, France operates a double fraud: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other on the reality of financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, she can make it appear that she spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has done the arbitration) could have a negative double impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it was enough to lend?) and in negotiations as developing countries are not fully aware of...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year's early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of compliance with its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape from the question of "additionality" or the way in which loans are accounted.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would be of a nature to increase the level of international confidence needed to advance in the discussions.
